# School-to-Career Transition (Malaysian Context)

## The Problem

Malaysian secondary students face a critical decision point after SPM (Sijil Pelajaran Malaysia, the national O-level equivalent). A [[creador-foundation]] study of **1,000+ students** found:

| Statistic | Finding |
|---|---|
| 80% | Have an ambition but lack essential knowledge about their chosen career |
| 70% | Do not actively research career options |
| Timing | Most only begin seriously planning post-SPM pathways *after* receiving SPM results |

The underlying dynamic: **"You can't be what you don't know."** Students from lower-resource backgrounds have less access to career information, professional networks, and guidance counsellors — creating unequal opportunity even among equally talented students.

## Why It Matters

Delayed or uninformed career planning leads to:
- Mismatch between subject choices and career goals
- Students defaulting to familiar/socially visible careers rather than exploring diverse options
- Poor preparation for post-secondary pathway decisions (TVET, pre-university, A-levels, etc.)

## The Schola Response

[[schola]] addresses this through free, self-directed digital tools:
- Career personality matching (RIASEC-based quiz)
- Subject-to-job mapping
- Detailed job guides with salary data and education pathways
- Gamified salary growth simulator

The platform is bilingual (English/BM) and free, designed to democratise career guidance across socioeconomic groups.

